{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489524"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:19:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"682"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/682"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.44,0.18,0.13,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31149"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/682"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17017"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6925"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7556"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31149"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are several components to the risk stratification for carcinoma of the prostate. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Once a prostate cancer is diagnosed, what information is required to complete the staging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["PSA, DRE, MRI","PSA, MRI, PSMA PET","PSA, DRE, MRI, CT abdo/pelvis, whole body bone scan","PSA, MRI, whole body bone scan","PSA, CT abdo/pelvis, whole body bone scan"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter diagnosing prostate cancer, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostate-specific antigen\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E(PSA)\u003C/strong\u003E in the serum is tested. \u003Cstrong\u003EProstate\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E with MRI-guided biopsy is increasingly used as a tool for defining risk status to evaluate the location and extent of prostate cancer, and the status of the pelvic lymph nodes. In clinical practice, \u003Cstrong\u003EPSMA PET \u003C/strong\u003Escans\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ehave taken over from CT abdominal/pelvis and whole body bone scans as it is much more accurate in identifying small volume lymph node and bony disease. This allows risk stratification of the disease and guides further treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProstate biopsy histopathology assesses the architecture of the prostate gland to determine a Gleason score. This indicates the tumours aggressiveness and is used to determine risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 6 = low\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 7 = intermediate\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGleason 8-10 = high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Prostate cancer can be risk stratified based on PSA, MRI, PSMA PET"],"references":["NCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology (NCCN Guidelines\u00ae): Prostate Cancer. Version 4.2018.","Parker C, Castro E, Fizazi K, Heidenreich A, Ost P, Procopio G, Tombal B, Gillessen S; ESMO Guidelines Committee. Electronic address: clinicalguidelines@esmo.org. Prostate cancer: ESMO Clinical Practice Guidelines for diagnosis, treatment and follow-up. Ann Oncol. 2020 Sep;31(9):1119-1134. doi: 10.1016/j.annonc.2020.06.011. Epub 2020 Jun 25. PMID: 32593798."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17017"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"